  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some books that a college going girl can read?",
  "response": "There are plenty of great books that a college-going girl might enjoy, spanning various genres \u2013 fiction, non-fiction, self-help, and more. Here are some recommendations:\n\n### Fiction\n1. **\"Eleanor Oliphant Is Completely Fine\" by Gail Honeyman** - A heartwarming and humorous story about loneliness and the importance of connection.\n2. **\"The Night Circus\" by Erin Morgenstern** - A beautifully written fantasy novel filled with magic, romance, and competition.\n3. **\"Little Fires Everywhere\" by Celeste Ng** - A compelling exploration of motherhood, race, and family dynamics in a suburban setting.\n4. **\"The Seven Husbands of Evelyn Hugo\" by Taylor Jenkins Reid** - A captivating story of an aging Hollywood icon recounting her glamorous yet tumultuous life.\n\n### Non-Fiction\n5. **\"Becoming\" by Michelle Obama** - An inspiring memoir from the former First Lady, detailing her life, values, and experiences.\n6. **\"Educated\" by Tara Westover** - A memoir about a woman's quest for knowledge, growing up in a strict and isolated family.\n7. **\"The Body Keeps the Score\" by Bessel van der Kolk** - An insightful look into trauma and its effects on the body and mind.\n\n### Self-Help & Personal Development\n8. **\"The Confidence Code\" by Katty Kay and Claire Shipman** - A guide to understanding and improving self-confidence, particularly for women.\n9. **\"Atomic Habits\" by James Clear** - A powerful book on how to build good habits and break bad ones, applicable to all aspects of life.\n10. **\"Daring Greatly\" by Bren\u00e9 Brown** - A thought-provoking look at the power of vulnerability and how it can lead to connection and innovation.\n\n### Classic Literature\n11. **\"Pride and Prejudice\" by Jane Austen** - A timeless story exploring love, social standing, and the role of women in society.\n12. **\"Jane Eyre\" by Charlotte Bront\u00eb** - A classic novel about a strong-willed woman pursuing her independence and love.\n\n### Young Adult (YA) & Contemporary\n13. **\"The Hate U Give\" by Angie Thomas** - A powerful novel about race, identity, and activism, inspired by the Black Lives Matter movement.\n14. **\"Divergent\" by Veronica Roth** - A dystopian series that tackles themes of identity, choice, and societal structure.\n\n### LGBTQ+ Themes\n15. **\"Simon vs. the Homo Sapiens Agenda\" by Becky Albertalli** - A heartwarming coming-of-age story about a gay teen navigating life and love.\n16. **\"Red, White & Royal Blue\" by Casey McQuiston** - A romantic comedy that explores a fictional relationship between the son of the U.S. president and a British prince.\n\n### Poetry\n17. **\"The Sun and Her Flowers\" by Rupi Kaur** - A collection of poetry exploring love, loss, trauma, and femininity.\n18. **\"Milk and Honey\" by Rupi Kaur** - A bestselling poetry collection about survival, femininity, and healing.\n\nThese books offer a range of themes and styles that can resonate with various experiences and interests, making them great choices for college students.",
